 the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montgomery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Sainte-Foy-de-Montgomery and Saint-Germain-de-Montgomery (Calvados). In Ireland this surname was present in the medieval period, died out, and was then reintroduced from Scotland in the 17th century. It has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>Mac Iomaire</b> and in Scotland as <b>Mac Gumaraid</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter de Montgomery was born in 1132, in Derbyshire, England as the son of William de Montgomery of Ecton. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Walter de Montgomery. He died before 1177."},"et":{"1132–Bef 1177":"1132–enne 1177","1132–1177":"1132–1177","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1156–1205":"1156–1205","1160–1205":"1160–1205","1105–1166":"1105–1166","1205":"1205","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","1156":"1156","Bef 1177":"enne 1177","before 1166":"enne 1166","1166":"1166","1177":"1177","1132":"1132","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","1160":"1160","Cubley, Uttoxeter, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ecton, Wellingborough, Northampton, England":"Ecton, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engl